<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/6abf9ac6974b498b16c00f79a573ef49> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#name> "EEN SCENE UIT DE BALLAD VAN HAMIR HATH : HET BESLISSEND GEVECHT" .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/6abf9ac6974b498b16c00f79a573ef49> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#description> "De Rajput cavalerie onder Hamir Hath doet een uitval en verslaat het leger van de Sultan. Op de tekening is het man-tot-man gevecht op zijn hoogste punt afgebeeld. De Sultan vecht vanuit zijn zetel op de rug van de olifant. Hamir Hath vecht op zijn paard en is nauwelijks van zijn generalen te onderscheiden. De vesting van Ranthambhor op de achtergrond lijkt verlaten. De Rajput vrouwen maken waarschijnlijk hun voorbereiding tot zelfverbranding, die de mogelijke nederlaag van hun leger zou volgen." .
<https://n2t.net/ark:/27023/6abf9ac6974b498b16c00f79a573ef49> <https://colonialcollections.nl/schema#material> "zwarte lijntekening op papier, met laagjes waterverf op verschillende plekken\r\nThe drawing was made on a sheet of Indian handmade paper. The paper has small charcoal particles, protruding fibres and fragments of blue thread or yarn that were part of the pulp composition and of the papermaking process. They indicate that the paper was made from recycled materials.\r\nThis work belongs to a series of five drawings depicting the Ballad of Amir Hath. On the recto, the primary outline was made with charcoal, the secondary drawing was carried out with red ink and the final outline was drawn with black ink. The support has been burnished on the recto and verso with two different tools: a wide and a narrow burnished (stone, glass, conch shell, etc). Some colour annotations were written in red ink\r\nOn the verso, there are a few lines of handwritten text in Nagari script which describe the scene painted on the recto. A label from the Vogel collection is adhered to in the bottom part and roughly translates what is written above in Nagari script.\r\nDue to the porosity of the paper and the lack of sizing and burnishing, the ink has migrated from the verso to the recto." .
